  "Hydrogen bonds prevent proteins from folding so they remain as straight chains at all times": "",
  "Hydrogen bonds remove water from proteins making them completely dry inside the body": "",
  "Hydrogen bonds form between different amino acids along a protein chain, helping to stabilize the protein's three-dimensional folded shape. This shape is critical because it determines the protein's function in the body.": "",
  "In winter, a lake freezes on the surface while fish survive in the liquid water below. How do hydrogen bonds make this possible?": "",
  "Fish generate enough body heat to prevent the water around them from freezing solid": "",
  "Hydrogen bonds cause ice to be less dense than water, so it floats and insulates the water below": "",
  "The salt content in lakes prevents the bottom water from reaching its freezing point": "",
  "Mud at the bottom of the lake releases heat that keeps the deeper water above freezing": "",
  "Hydrogen bonds in ice create an open hexagonal structure that is less dense than liquid water, so ice floats. The floating ice layer acts as insulation, preventing the entire lake from freezing and allowing aquatic life to survive in the liquid water below.": "",
  "A student dissolves table salt (NaCl) in water very easily. How do hydrogen bonds in water help dissolve ionic compounds like salt?": "",
  "Water molecules are nonpolar, so they break apart the ionic bonds through physical force": "",
  "The partial charges on polar water molecules surround and pull apart the Na+ and Cl- ions": "",
  "Hydrogen bonds in water make it extremely hot, which melts the salt crystals completely": "",
  "Water chemically reacts with salt to form a new compound that is invisible in the solution": "",
  "Water's polarity, which comes from the same electronegativity difference that enables hydrogen bonding, allows it to dissolve salt. The partially negative oxygen atoms attract Na+ ions, and the partially positive hydrogen atoms attract Cl- ions, pulling the crystal apart.": "",
  "A student notices that rubbing alcohol evaporates from their skin much faster than water, even though both are liquids at room temperature. What does this suggest about their hydrogen bonding?": "",
  "Rubbing alcohol has stronger hydrogen bonds than water, causing faster evaporation rates": "",
  "Water has stronger hydrogen bonds than rubbing alcohol, making water harder to evaporate": "",
  "Both liquids have the same hydrogen bonding strength but different molecular colors": "",
  "Rubbing alcohol has no intermolecular forces at all, which is why it evaporates quickly": "",
  "Water evaporates more slowly because it has stronger and more extensive hydrogen bonding than rubbing alcohol. Water can form up to four hydrogen bonds per molecule, while rubbing alcohol can form fewer. This means more energy is needed to evaporate water.": "",
  "Plants transport water from their roots to their leaves, sometimes many meters above the ground. How do hydrogen bonds help make this possible?": "",
  "Hydrogen bonds make water heavy enough to be pushed upward by root pressure alone": "",
  "Cohesion from hydrogen bonds keeps water in a continuous column, and adhesion to vessel walls helps pull it upward": "",
  "Plants heat the water in their roots until it evaporates and rises as steam to the leaves": "",
  "Hydrogen bonds in water create an anti-gravity effect that naturally lifts water upward": "",
  "Water moves up through plants by transpiration pull. Hydrogen bonds create cohesion (water molecules stick together in a continuous chain) and adhesion (water molecules stick to the walls of xylem vessels), allowing water to be pulled upward from roots to leaves.": ""
